{\*\cs11\fs20 , and }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Old School Essentials}{\*\cs11\fs20 . I\rquote m going to use these highlighted commentary sections to rant and ramble and add more context. Skip them if you\rquote re just looking for rules.\par \ldblquote Strict Time Records\rdblquote  is a Gygaxian reference to the first edition }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Advanced Dungeons and Dragons Dungeon Master\rquote s Guide }{\*\cs11\fs20 which claimed that without meaningful time records, you couldn\rquote t play the game effectively. There is much truth to this, but I\rquote ve never been very satisfied with the particular way time is handled in the various }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i D&D}{\*\cs11\fs20  editions. One of the core goals of this system is to make time pressure and resource management central to the game while keeping the fiddly bits manageable. That\rquote s kind of my jam. I wrote another game called }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Wrath of the Autarch}{\*\cs11\fs20  which is fun if you want a really deep dive on domain management. Word of warning: }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i WotA}{\*\cs11\fs20  is very fiddly, and feels more like a boardgame.\par There is also a primary design goal to hew close to the 1981 }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Basic/Expert D&D}{\*\cs11\fs20  core popular in Old School Renaissance (OSR) circles. In particular, I\rquote m interested in using hexcrawl content like }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Barrowmaze}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Hot Springs Island}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Night\rquote s Dark Terror}
