{\*\cs11\fs20 }{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 \par }{\*\cs11\fs20 The }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i natural}{\*\cs11\fs20  above refers to a d20 roll that shows the }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 exact}{\*\cs11\fs20  number in question, regardless of ability score modifiers. For example, if a player has a +2 modifier to a roll, and rolls an 18, the result is }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 not}{\*\cs11\fs20  a critical even though the total is a 20. Only an unmodified roll of 20 is a critical.\par }
\pard\plain \s4\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\cbpat0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 I really wanted to keep the widely known d20 interpretations of 1 as a fumble or massive failure and 20 as a critical success. The roll under ability score OSR variants like }
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Black Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Whitehack}{\*\cs11\fs20  are cleanly designed, but there\rquote s a ton of cultural inertia around what rolling a 20 means. I also really like the historical precedent of rolling 3d6 straight down for ability scores during character creation. Using roll under with that approach makes for wildly ineffective or overpowered characters without tweaking how ability scores are generated. Keeping modifiers between -3 and +3 and success on 8+ means that even very high or low ability scores aren\rquote t going to wildly skew success or failure. At the worst, there\rquote s still about a 50% chance of success.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Advantage and Disadvantage\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Some situations can result in a test roll having }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i advantage}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i
disadvantage}{\*\cs11\fs20 . If a player has advantage on a test, they roll two dice and take the highest result. If they have disadvantage, they roll two dice and take the lowest result. This frequently applies to tests (d20 rolls), but could apply to any dice rolls, of any dice type, as specified. If a player has both advantage and disadvantage on a roll, they cancel each other out and the die is rolled straight.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Keep Criticals and Fumbles!\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Some situations may allow a player to modify a test result in various ways, or re-roll the result. This may allow them to change a miss into a weak success or a weak success into a strong success. However, }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 fumbles and criticals can\rquote t be altered after the roll}{\*\cs11\fs20 . That\rquote s the result!\par }\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 General Tests\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Sometimes a test is called for that does not use any ability score modifier. This is referred to as a }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i
general test}{\*\cs11\fs20 . Frequently this is rolled by the gamemaster, with the results being interpreted based on the degree of success or failure. Random events in the dungeon and wilderness are an example of this sort of test.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Saves\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i Saves}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i saving throws}{\*\cs11\fs20  are tests which are reactive. They work the same way as other tests, but they tend to be driven by the gamemaster or as a consequence of some action taken by the player. For instance, if a poisonous beast bites a character, they may have to make a save using their Constitution. As usual, an 8+ is successful. Degrees of success and failure may be used to further distinguish results as normal.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f0\fs28\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs28 Procedures\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 The game consists of an ongoing dialog between the players. The gamemaster gets the ball rolling by setting scenes and situations that the characters find themselves in.\par }
\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 As this narrative unfolds, some fictional situations have explicit steps to follow when they occur. These steps are called }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i procedures}{\*\cs11\fs20 . Most procedures use tests, and include results for each degree of success and failure. If there isn\rquote t an entry for a particular result, assume nothing happens. Some procedures specify which ability score to use, with phrases like }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 test Str}{\*\cs11\fs20  or }{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 make a Cha test}{\*\cs11\fs20 .\par The choice of which procedure to use is not just up to the fictional situation, however! There may be multiple procedures that apply to a situation: some are simple and some are involved. Choosing which to use depends on what sounds fun and interesting to everyone at the table.\par }
\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Overcome and Create Advantage\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Two core procedures are }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i overcome}{\*\cs11\fs20  and }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i create advantage}{\*\cs11\fs20
. These workshorse procedures will drive the narrative forward when no other procedures quite work. They will become second nature.\par }
\pard\plain \s7\f2\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Overcome\par }\pard\plain \s8\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb90\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keep\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i When you wish to accomplish a task that is both }{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i uncertain}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i  and }{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i
interesting}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , make a test using a relevant ability. Briefly outline what the character is attempting to do, waiting until after the roll to fill in details. On a\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Critical}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , the character has amazing success! Either the effect is much greater or it takes less time than anticipated.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Strong success}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , the character succeeds at the task.\par }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i Weak success}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i
, the character succeeds at the task, but there is a complication of some sort! Perhaps resources are used or a different problem has emerged.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Miss}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , the character fails at the task.\par }{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Fumble}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , whatever can go wrong, does. This is the worst possible result.}
{\*\cs11\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s7\f2\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs24 Create Advantage\par }\pard\plain \s8\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb90\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keep\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Choose an ally to help with a test. Helping takes the same amount of time as the target ally\rquote s action. Narrate how your character is helping and test the most relevant ability. On a\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Critical}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , the ally\rquote s test is made with advantage, and they receive an additional +2 on the result.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Strong success}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , the ally\rquote s test is made with advantage, and they receive an additional +1 on the result.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Weak success}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , your help is appreciated! The ally\rquote s test is made with advantage.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Miss}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , there are too many cooks in the kitchen! The ally does not get advantage and no one else can create an advantage for this test.\par }
{\*\cs15\fs20\b\i Fumble}{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i , you\rquote re doing more harm than good! The ally\rquote s test is made with disadvantage and no one else can create advantage for this test.}
{\*\cs11\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s4\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\cbpat0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Inevitably in role-playing games, one player wishes to help another one. Create Advantage was crafted for this reason. The name of this procedure, along with the name for Overcome, were stolen from }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Fate Core}{\*\cs11\fs20 . The goal here is to provide an avenue for characters to help each other in a careful, deliberate manner.\par It\rquote s important to note that creating an advantage takes as much time as the action the advantage is for. So, in combat, creating an advantage takes a short amount of time, since actions are measured in ten second rounds. During wilderness exploration, creating an advantage takes longer, since actions in wilderness exploration are measured in four hour watches.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f0\fs28\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs28 Minigames\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Some procedures are involved, and inject strategy into }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20 . These procedures are called }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i minigames}{\*\cs11\fs20 . Minigames have players take turns and choose from a variety of options during their turn. The minigames in }
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  are }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i wilderness exploration}{\*\cs11\fs20 , }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i
ocean exploration}{\*\cs11\fs20 , }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i dungeon exploration}{\*\cs11\fs20 , }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i court}{\*\cs11\fs20 , }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i combat}{\*\cs11\fs20 , and }{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i downtime}{\*\cs11\fs20 .\par It\rquote s possible to resolve fictional situations using just overcome and create advantage, but }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  is more fun with the time pressure and difficult choices that minigames provide. Also, you paid for 80 pages of rules, not two!\par }
\pard\plain \s4\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\cbpat0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Many of the procedures in }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  look like moves from }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i
Apocalypse World}{\*\cs11\fs20 . }{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Apocalypse World}{\*\cs11\fs20  burst forth on the RPG scene in 2010 and had a major impact on game design. There are quite a few }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i PbtA}{\*\cs11\fs20  (Powered by the Apocalypse) games, which leverage, to varying degrees of success, the tech from }
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Apocalypse World}{\*\cs11\fs20 . Moves are also mechanical widgets triggered by fictional situations, although they usually aren\rquote t nested within more involved turn based procedures. They also tend to be less prescriptive than what I\rquote m doing here, so I didn\rquote t want to use that word.\par I like the free flowing behavior of moves to push the fiction in all sorts of interesting directions. However, I also really like structured minigames, such as Duel of Wits in }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Burning Wheel}{\*\cs11\fs20  or Combat in }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i The One Ring}{\*\cs11\fs20 . Those minigames need turns to work well. Turns have an advantage over moves in that the spotlight tends to get deliberately shared more, and minigames add tactical diversity and strategy. Relying too much on minigames may result in an overly regimented game that may become a little dry. However, only relying on moves makes the game less strategic, which I don\rquote t personally enjoy as much.\par }
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  mixes free flowing procedures with minigames. }{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Apocalypse World}
{\*\cs11\fs20  purists might blanch at this approach, but I see no incompatibility from switching between the freeform \ldblquote talk in the funny voices\rdblquote  parts of rpgs and the \ldblquote win at a game\rdblquote  parts of rpgs. It\rquote s easy enough to tell which is which and when to use either.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f0\fs28\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs28 Spotlight Player\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  occasionally has choices and die rolls that aren\rquote t directly related to any particular character. A }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i spotlight player}{\*\cs11\fs20  makes these choices and die rolls. The spotlight player should be chosen at the beginning of the session. Rotate the spotlight around, so that players alternate the responsibility. Occasionally the spotlight player endures further complications or hardships for their character! Being in the spotlight isn\rquote t always a purely beneficial experience.\par }
\pard\plain \s5\f0\fs28\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs28 Usage Dice\par }\pard\plain \s3\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i Usage dice}{\*\cs11\fs20  are a general purpose tracking mechanism heavily featured in }{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Lavender Hack}
{\*\cs11\fs20 . Usage dice change die type based on situations in the game. This forms a ladder of sorts, going from d2 at the lowest to d12 at the highest.\par }
