{\*\cs11\fs20 A d20 is used for the lowest step. A usage die can never be above a d12 or below a d20.\par Usage dice may reflect an }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 amount}{\*\cs11\fs20  of something, in which case the d12 represents having a lot of it and the d20 represents just scraping by. For example, a d12 food die means the characters have plenty of food of all different kinds, and a d20 means they have a few very questionable berries found while foraging.\par Usage dice may reflect the }
{\*\cs14\fs20\b\i0 quality}{\*\cs11\fs20  of something, in which case the d12 represents something of the highest quality, while a d20 represents something very shoddy and makeshift. For example, if used for light, a d12 is a number of lanterns with plenty of oil, while a d2 is a torch scrapped together from a torn bit of clothing.\par If the rules instruct you to }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i step up}{\*\cs11\fs20  a usage die, you increase the die by one step. For example, a d8 would get swapped out with a d10. If the rules instruct you to }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i step down}{\*\cs11\fs20  a usage die, you lower the die by one step. For example, a d8 would get swapped with a d6. There are a variety of ways and reasons usage dice are stepped up and down. A d12 can\rquote t be stepped up and a d20 can\rquote t be stepped down. A d20 usage die is referred to as }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i broken}{\*\cs11\fs20 .\par }\pard\plain \s6\f0\fs24\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\b0\i\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
