{\*\cs11\fs20 If players are forced to roll a d20 usage die, the result is almost never good! Each type of usage die has a set of general test results that are used for this purpose. Rolling a d20 usage die is referred to as }
{\*\cs16\fs20\b\i making a usage save}{\*\cs11\fs20 . A usage save is also made if the d20 die is stepped down for some reason.\par The spotlight player rolls the usage die and looks up the related save results to determine the value and what happens!\par }
\pard\plain \s4\f1\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl288\slmult1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\cbpat0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\*\cs11\fs20 Usage dice come from the game }{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Black Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20 , although they are also used very effectively and extensively in }
{\*\cs13\fs20\b0\i Macchiato Monsters}{\*\cs11\fs20 . In }{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i Black Hack}{\*\cs11\fs20  they lower on a 1-2. I used the }
{\*\cs12\fs20\b0\i MM}{\*\cs11\fs20  version, which is where the 1-3 comes from. Stepping down on a 1-3 ensures a little more movement, even for larger die types.\par I love the concept of usage dice, although getting them to function well as an economy is one of the most active parts of development. Who knows, maybe they won\rquote t be as good of a fit as simple counters. In order for them to be viable, they need to be rolled frequently!\par }
